Dr Moukhaiber is an amazing attending, her rounds in the PICU are organized and thorough.
She is always accessible and available to answer our queries and to address our concerns.

Dr. Majdalani is a wonderful attending who shows a lot of concern for the patients and the staff. 
Plans are always made for the patient's benefit during her rounds in the early morning.
She support us in every circumstance, pays attention to our issues, responds to them, and works to find solutions.
Dr Ismail is always present when a support is needed.

Dr Sbaity's conduct can be borderline unprofessional, if not downright disrespectful and degrading at times. Working with her is emotionally draining. She is a good academic and a good surgeon, if only her attitude and conduct with the residents could be improved.
We are lucky to have Dr Khoury on board and it is a great privilege to learn from his expertise.

Great skills.

Respectful.

Respectful.

Dr Haddad is a professional vascular surgeon who works responsibly with all his patients, follows up well on them, respects all the staff, appreciates our work. I have been working with him for several years and I am impressed by his attitude and work.

Dr Hoballah is a highly professional vascular surgeon and chairman who works responsibly with all his patients, follows up well on them pre and post operatively, respects all the staff, appreciates our work. I have been working with him for several years and I am impressed by his attitude and work.
Such an amazing character, highly professional, a role model, working with Dr. Khouzami is always a pleasure. He respects nurses / nurses workflow. Highly cooperative.

Such a talented physician with great knowledge and communication skills, he is the number 1 attending physician according to my perspective. He is the only physician who teaches us about patient cases and discusses the treatment plan with us. Proud to work with Dr Bassem.

Role model

Dr Tanios has shown himself to be a great physician, nephrologist, patient–advocate and mentor/educator.
He has wonderful beside manners, listens and help patients with all their needs, always conducts himelf in utmost professionalism.
A true pleasure to have Bassem as a member of the nephrology team

Dr Daouk is simply a great senior physician, patient–advocate and mentor. She takes it personally upon herself to assist patients in need of help, be it by advocating for them, supporting request for helping them or raising funds for the Kidney Patient fund from donors. We are all indebted to her efforts and consistent advocacy for all patients.
She is a wonderful mentor to fellows. She is highly liked and respected by her patients and by staff alike.

Dr Mallat is a very experienced senior nephrologist and internist, a true academician and role mode. He maintains a very busy practice, attending to all its needs and demands, and providing fisrt–rate medical care and service to patients. He is highly respected as a nephrologist, as a medical staff member, as a faculty member with seniority and simply as a trusted colleague. He participates and enriches all the activies of the Division and plays an active role in the educational mission of the Division.

Dr Medawwar is a seasoned, highly experienced, senior nephrologist and internist. He maintains a busy high volume practice to which he devotes all necessary efforts, meeting needs of patients at all times. He is a wonderful physician, person and colleague who is highluy respected by patients and staff alike. He is always at the ready to help. He conducts himself in most professional manner.

I have providing renal care in the inpatient setting through consultations and as Admitting Physician, in the outpatient clinic at ACC, in the Mamdouha el–Sayed Bobst Hemodialysis Unit, maintaining an active busy regional practice. I have also been providing administrative support for the outpatient and inpatient dialysis program, CRRT, Peritoneal Dialysis, Hypertension lab among other services. This is in addition to coaching and mentoring of fellows, residents and students. I have also worked closely with Dr Daouk to administer the Patient Support funds and aid those in need.
Dr. Hamza is highly knowledgeable and delicated to patients, respect all staff members and always follow up about patients conditions and treatments
A great respectful surgeon and mentor, dedicated to teaching and patient care.
despite his busy schedule, he keeps up with his clinical and research work within the highest standards of ethics, respect to staff, dedication to teaching and patient care.

despite being overloaded with clinical work and administrative one, he does his best to accommodate between all tasks within his limits. Staff and residents know him very well that he is very serious when it deals with work and patient care and that it has nothing to do with friendships. Patients love him and get only positive feedback from them.

Thank you for this comprehensive survey. I hope it will be used to provide constructive and professional feedback on my actual behaviour. And I wish that all people that I work with will fill it in an honest way.
I am known to come to the OR before any other employee, to carry the patient and wheel them when escorts are not around. Delaying patients is not in my dictionary

I have known Dr Yazbeck since my appointment at AUBMC spanning over 25 years now..
Dr Yazbeck and myself have shared and continue to share the care of many patients. She has always been welcoming to discussions we do together regarding patient care. She undoubtedly is accommodating to last minute patients to be seen and always with a smile. Echoes from patients I refer to her are positive. We also share work on studies as well as the Nutrition Committee that handles new emerging recommendations and critical care nutrition guidelines as well as highly specialised nutrition support intervention. She is indeed much respected and loved by the medical students and resident community.
Indeed a professional respectful attending–one of the best. I personally look forward to working with her many more years to come

I have worked with Dr Karam for the past years since 1998. Initially I have known her when she used to be consulted for the inherited metabolic cases at AUBMC to then officially join our medical centre. Since then I share with her all patients enrolled in the IMDP program/clinic. I also share with her several publications on our patients. She is someone who welcomes discussions and works diligently to the best of her patients. I do call her anytime to attend to the many patient issues we have regarding the difficult diseases we deal in the metabolic conditions. Moreover we do share a course we teach together at FAFS (medical Nutrition Therapy) and sixths was the first of its kind–a course we designed to be co–taught by her as the medical provider and myself as the Biblical Dietitian. The feed back from the course is amazing. So is the feedback from medical students and residents who deal with her. Dr Karam is indeed a professional, respectful and ethical physician whom I enjoy working with and look forward to continue doing..
This is a self–assessment! at least this is what i believe about myself.

Dr. Khatib is a true leader who has worked conscientiously, efficiently & professionaly to move our department & all our staff to higher level of knowledge & skills based on updated evidence–based science & medical research. I am writing to provide feedback on my experiences working with Dr. Sbaity. 
During our interactions, I have observed instances where Dr. Sbaity has exhibited unprofessional behavior, including dishonesty and disrespect. It is essential for a medical professional to maintain trust and integrity with patients and colleagues alike, and these behaviors have created a challenging working environment.

To foster a more positive and effective work environment, I would recommend that Dr. Sbaity undergo further training or development in communication skills, empathy, and professionalism. It is important for all team members to uphold the highest standards of ethical conduct and respectful communication.

I appreciate the opportunity to provide this evaluation, and I hope that these concerns can be addressed to ensure a more harmonious and productive work environment.

Dr. Yunis is an exceptional physician. He is known for his outstanding clinical skills and his dedication to providing the highest quality of care to his patients. Dr. Yunis is always professional and courteous in his interactions with staff and families, and he is an excellent communicator who takes the time to listen to the parents and discuss their concerns. Teaches the fellows and other team members (interns, residents...) during inpatient rounds
Teaches the fellows mainly during the weekly leukemia/lymphoma rounds
Punctual in his inpatient round timing, efficient in making decisions, explains clearly the situation to the patients no matter how complicated they might be

However, he puts pressure on the fellows on things that are not their responsibility (e.g. he asks the fellows to ask the oncology pharmacists to stay after hours to prepare chemotherapy despite knowing that they are understaffed and all the senior pharmacists already quit the hospital; asks for bone marrow results in 24h even when he knows that the hospital only has 1 heme–pathologist and might take him days to reach the slides of that particular patient...)
Sometimes can be hurtful in his comments even when they are made as a joke

In my humble opinion, he does not give adequate time for inpatients and their families.
He completely relies on fellows to see his new patients and fill their histories (e.g. might cancel his clinic when he doesn't have a fellow, or adds several drop in new cases whenever a fellow is assigned with him that same day). Nevertheless, he teaches the fellows during the tumor boards and clinic rotations.

He never stops helping the patients in any way he can (providing free medications...), Nevertheless:

– Does not give completely accurate information to the patients, which in turn might affect their decision (e.g. tells a patient who needs stem cell transplant that transplant related mortality is 1.5% when in fact it reaches 20%).
– Talks to medical team members/nurses in a demeaning way (even if he's saying the words as a joke, they are hurtful) during the inpatient specially on Tuesdays when he's the only attending rounding. For instance, he tells patients that the students only care about going to the beach and don't pay attention to patient care. He once told a patient he saw for the first time that the fellow rotating with them will take her stem cells and sell them in the black market, and the patient burst into tears. He makes occasional jokes about fat people and those from different cultures, and the list goes on.
– He tells the patients that the management of their case (by his colleagues in the same team) are completely wrong even when it's not.
– He once agreed to treat a patient without telling her she has cancer, forcing us (the fellows) to lie to her when consenting her for chemotherapy or bone marrow biopsy.
– He gives himself credit for things he did not do.
– He changes his mind when the decision he took impacts the patients negatively, and denies taking that decision in the first place and blames the team.
– He insists on his decisions despite knowing that they might hurt the patients: for instance a well educated patient with 17p deletion Multiple Myeloma (high risk) pentarefractory had cord compression because of major disease progression. He refused to tell the patient or his family how serious the situation is, and insisted on operating on the patient instead of giving systemic treatment. He eventually changed his mind, but the patient deteriorated and got intubated and transferred to the ICU because of the delay in management.

He has a good heart, but unfortunately lacks communication skills and good clinical sense.

She is an exemplary human and physician in terms of knowledge and patient care, however:

– Sometimes, she replies late to our messages (waits until finishes her clinic), which might affect patient care negatively
– She frequently changes her mind about decisions she already took on patients (chemotherapy, transplant, admission, discharge..), which frustrates us and the whole team

I am writing to express my concerns regarding Dr. Barazi's role as Program Director. Throughout my residency, I have experienced significant challenges under her leadership that have profoundly affected my well–being and professional development.

Dr. Barazi has displayed favoritism towards certain residents, overlooking valid concerns raised by myself and others regarding bullying and exclusion. Despite being aware of these issues, she evaluated me based on biased reports without addressing the underlying problems. This approach has left me feeling insecure and unfairly treated.

Her management style has included threats of probation, frequent exams, and unnecessary medical interventions, such as prescribing antidepressants without proper evaluation. This has exacerbated my anxiety and isolated me from the resident community.

Moreover, Dr. Barazi's unprofessional conduct includes inappropriate remarks about my performance, discussions with other residents about my evaluations, and unjustified grading discrepancies despite positive feedback from other attendings.

I believe Dr. Barazi's actions are detrimental to the program and residents' well–being. I urge you to investigate these concerns and take appropriate action to ensure a fair and supportive environment for all residents.

In my humble opinion, having been part of this department for six years, I truly and honestly believe that Dr. Korban is one of the most, if not the most, valuable and exceptionally skilled members and pillars of this department. Dr. Korban exemplifies time management and efficiency. She is sought after from every borough, county, and district in Lebanon, as well as surrounding countries. She is consistently referred challenging and critical cases from many successful and renowned surgeons. This is not only because Dr. Korban embodies ethics and compassion, treating every patient with the utmost respect, honesty, and professionalism, but also because she is a truly gifted mind and surgeon. Her skills always astonish us, as she possesses extremely advanced surgical skills and surgical IQ, which gives her the confidence to safely approach the rarest and most challenging cases that have been unsuccessfully treated in many centers.
Dr. Korban always responds to our calls, regardless of the case, day, or time, even when she is not on call. She is the first to rush in if a certain attending is not reachable, making us residents feel supported and protected. No matter the urgency, she is next to us, ensuring the utmost safety and advanced treatment for any patient. Dr. Korban has matched her exceptional training in skull base surgery and rhinology with becoming an allergy expert, forming an extremely rare and well–rounded physician capable of tackling the most advanced cases from A to Z.
Dr. Korban is an inspiration and a true trailblazer. She frequently participates in worldwide renowned conferences, invited countless times as a guest speaker, always delivering new and cutting–edge advancements in her field. She has always treated all the staff with the utmost respect, always distributing gifts of gratitude from patients to the staff, especially the nursing staff. Every nurse fights for time with Dr. Korban, at least from what I have seen, because she is so attentive, caring, and respectful. Dr. Korban's clinic is a critical part of this program, offering an in–depth look at patient care in the best possible way. She consistently follows the latest evidence–based guidelines, always offering maximal medical therapy before opting for surgery. Despite her fearlessness and skill, she is ethical, ensuring the patient receives optimal treatment and leaving no doubt about what more she could have done.
Dr. Korban stays late during clinical days because she always accepts drop–ins, urgent cases, and late patients, often sacrificing extra hours from her personal life. She is always critical in ensuring we improve and are efficient in the OR, teaching us amazing techniques and challenging us every step of the way.

Unfortunately, Dr. Mourad never gave me a fair chance. He came to the program with preconceived notions about me, constantly stating that I have poor relationships with staff, residents, patients, and attendings. The truth is, I have received many texts and messages praising my support and guidance from various team members throughout the year. I have a good relationship with most of the attendings, except for Dr. Mourad and one other. I have been praised by staff for going out of my way to help them, even with personal problems, and for my patient care during OPD and OR.
Dr. Mourad has taught me a lot, even though he has always shown signs of not liking me personally through passive–aggressive comments. He constantly waits for any small misunderstanding or technical problem to report to the program director. He never personally talks to me or discusses issues at the time but instead writes a report on everything he sees wrong with me. Dr. Mourad showed great disparity between the chiefs, even though the chiefs themselves were on good terms. This was evident in many events reported to the program director.
For example, he would talk aggressively with Mounir and not respect his surroundings, while never doing so with Nadine, even when discussing similar situations. It was clear that this was due to Dr. Mourad's constant need for Dr. Nadine's father to assist him in complicated cases, while he felt there would be no repercussions for talking down to Dr. Bousaab. This was especially evident in two cases. In one, Dr. Bousaab complained about how he was addressed when asking a scheduling question and was berated in front of patients and staff. The program director's response was, "Dr. Mourad was mad about something, and it came out on you." In a second event, Dr. Bousaab was berated in the OR for imaging that was not uploaded to the appropriate system, which was not his fault. When Dr. Bousaab informed the program director, he was told it would be taken care of, only to receive no response. Instead, a few days later, he was called to take a warning due in part to an email from Dr. Mourad concerning events dating back months, seemingly in retaliation for the complaint.
I have never seen such actions in a reputable hospital and am saddened that Dr. Mourad went down this path. He seemed to be ethical and have a good moral compass. He always recognized my surgical skills and mentioned them positively. It's a shame he didn't have the self–confidence to judge for himself. It's truly a shame he was dragged down such a path that has become so evident to all the residents, even if they are too fearful to mention it themselves. I have been fearful for years to stand up to these actions, fearing losing my job or any further opportunities. I hope Dr. Mourad changes things around. He has great potential but seems to lack a strong independent moral personality and tends to follow the path of least resistance when judging residents. His behavior shows a tendency to pick on and bully those he perceives as weak, which is detrimental to the mental health of many residents.

Having had the fortune and privilege to train under and learn from Dr. Hadi, I now have a deepened respect for the teaching aspect of a residency program. Dr. Hadi is an unparalleled mentor who is irreplaceable. I feel an unwavering sense of security in cases with Dr. Hadi due to his exceptional breadth of knowledge and experience across all aspects of our specialty, despite his specialization as a magnificent rhinologist and skull base surgeon. Dr. Hadi is also one of the most compassionate and ethical physicians I have had the honor of working with. Not once has Dr. Hadi made me feel any different from my co–chief, Dr. Nadin El Hadi, his own daughter. On the contrary, he consistently treats us equally and ensures we learn to work together and with others more effectively. He has even made sure that I scrubbed in on major cases assigned to Dr. Nadin, as is her right as chief of the week.
Dr. Hadi has always been present and ready for any urgent cases and consultations, even when he is not on call or in the area. I have seen Dr. Hadi come to the rescue in many urgent cases being handled by other attendings in our department, always willing to help and lend his knowledge. As residents, we all know we can count on Dr. Hadi to tackle the most challenging cases that have been given up on and to treat them with dignity, always giving his all.
The rhinology program developed by Dr. Hadi alongside Dr. Korban is one of the best and most advanced I have seen. Dr. Hadi and Dr. Korban use all their resources and experts in different fields to conduct an amazing collaborative learning experience that provides us with various international schools of thought. As residents, my colleagues and I have often discussed how amazing this program is and how privileged we are to be a part of it. This program connects us with world–renowned surgeons globally. Dr. Korban and Dr. Hadi both stay hours after lectures, volunteering their precious time for us to ask questions and discuss topics. This support and commitment to teaching is unmatched.
On a humanitarian, ethical, and compassionate level, Dr. Hadi has always shown me encouragement and support. He has always been fair, providing constructive feedback and never letting me get away with any mistakes in my notes, knowledge, or how I handle urgent consults. Even at 3 a.m. on a consult, he ensures the patient is safe and afterwards goes over every step, discussing what was done right or wrong and how to improve in the most constructive and motivating way.
Dr. Hadi is truly irreplaceable and would be a great loss if he ever left this program, especially in these times when he holds a significant burden in the department. Dr. Hadi is a rare and remarkable type of surgeon who is well–rounded and dedicated to teaching, always taking more of his time to allow us more exposure and hands–on experience. He is truly one of the greatest mentors, physicians, surgeons, and men I have had the pleasure of meeting.

The current institutional environment incentivizes physicians to see an increasing number of patients in order to boost their income. While this approach may enhance financial performance in the short term, it often comes at the expense of patient care quality and overall satisfaction. This high–pressure setting can lead to rushed consultations, reduced time for thorough patient evaluations, and a lack of personalized care.
To protect an enhance the institutions reputation and ensure a higher standard of patient care, a shift in priorities is essential. Emphasizing patient satisfaction and comprehensive care should be the primary focus. By doing so, the institution can foster a more positive and trusting relationship between patients and healthcare providers.
Additionally, many physicians are currently neglecting to write an appropriate note and update patients' problem lists and medication records in the Epic system. This oversight can result in significant medical errors, including the prescription of duplicate medications and the occurrence of adverse drug interactions. Maintaining accurate and up–to–date records is crucial for ensuring patient safety and delivering effective care.

The real challenge in my practice is managing an overbooked schedule filled with extra patients, compounded by the high volume of messages that patients can easily generate thanks to the accessibility of our communication systems.

Because of my challenging job, many times the parents come anxious to my clinic. sometimes the parents do not accept the diagnosis of their children. Sometimes  the parents d not accept any small comment about their child . Sometimes the father and mother  come with conflicts between them which lowers their cooperation with the treating team and negatively affect their child (child neglect).
Also in one instance I gave an objective comment in a meeting which I discovered later to  negatively impact on one of my colleagues because of a personal issue related to that colleague.
With time I am learning to limit talking with patients and colleagues to the minimum necessary, to be objective most of the time, to talk about patients in closed rooms and to refer to psychiatry and child protection committee whenever the parents or children need it.
All this control of the situation can not be achieved without work life balance, something that I missed during the war time which caused me a lot of stress in clinical, research, teaching duties. From now on, I will be taking more vacations to decrease burn out. I also started daily physical exercise and writing down on a notebook the issues that bother me.
